ental, philosophical perspective, she recounts her journey from the Great Hungarian Plain to the extermination camp of Auschwitz-Birkenau, the forced labour camp of Münchmühle, and back. The English edition includes a new introduction by historians Éva Kovács and Judith Szapor, the original prefaces to the Hungarian and German editions, an essay on the Münchmüle Camp by Fritz Brinkman-Frisch, and extensive notes providing historical and cultural context for Fahidi’s narrative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vPersonal narratives. 0aJewszHungaryvBiography. 0aJews, HungarianvBiography. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAuschwitz.  aDebrecen.  aHolocaust and women.  aHolocaust memoir.  aHolocaust testimony.  aHolocaust.  aHungarian Jewish life before WWII.  aHungary.  aMünchmüle.  aconcentration camps.  aghettos in Hungary.  aslave labour.1 aAly, Götz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrinkmann-Frisch, Fritz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahidi, Éva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGábor, György, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKovács, Éva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSzapor, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSzapor, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753625140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487536251423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487536251.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Pa